            text: 'Started to look at the environmental spawner side of things today. I decided to make this an event type system, and so far this appears to work. The main idea is that the displayed message and the actual weather effect should match, rather than just firing random text at the HUD and hoping the game state makes sense.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'The rain weather event mostly behaved, although once it spawned the rain-hitting-the-ground particle effect, it decided it was not going to turn that effect off. This turned out to be an oversight on my part. I had created the particle box, but had never copied it into the Weather Effect Controller so it could be stopped along with the rest of the rain effects.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'That was a quick and relatively painless fix. The weather stack now has the main rain effect, the player foot splash effect, and the ground splash particle effect all starting and stopping together.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'note',
        title: 'Weather cleanup',
        text: 'Environmental events now better separate message type from weather effect. Rain starts from the rain event, other environmental messages no longer incorrectly trigger rain, and all rain-related particle systems are stopped by the WeatherEffectController.',
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Next on the list was investigating the ',
          },
          {
            text: 'meanieProjectileSpawner',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: '. The way the meanies work now is that they have a primary sprite with three empty objects to the side: ',
          },
          {
            text: 'GroundCheck',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: ', ',
          },
          {
            text: 'WallCheck',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: ', and ',
          },
          {
            text: 'meanieProjectileSpawner',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: '.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Right now I have a script named ',
          },
          {
            text: 'MeaniePatrol',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: ', and when that flips the meanie, it also flips the check objects. So my first thought was that it should be as simple as making sure the ',
          },
          {
            text: 'meanieProjectileSpawner',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: ' flips as well.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'figure',
        src: '/images/games/courier-16/I-Blame-Myself.jpg',
        alt: 'A Ghostbusters meme showing the caption I Blame Myself, used after discovering the meanie projectile spawn point was correct but the projectile direction code was not updating.',
        caption:
          'The projectile spawner was flipping correctly. The projectile direction was not. I blame myself.',
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Well, it turns out everything was flipping correctly. The entire prefab flips, and the projectile spawner is part of that prefab. Someone had simply never added the code to change the projectile direction when the meanie flipped.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Added and updated the code so the shooter reads the current patrol direction and launches the projectile that way. Now everyone is firing projectiles all over the place, but importantly, they are firing them in the correct direction.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'note',
        title: 'Combat cleanup',
        text: 'Meanie projectile spawners were already flipping correctly with the prefab. The missing piece was making MeanieShooter use the current MeaniePatrol direction instead of always firing from right to left.',
      },
      {
        type: 'next',
        title: 'Player Animation and Enemy Tuning',
        text: 'Next up is likely player animation, shooter timing balance, and deciding which meanies should patrol, shoot, or roam around the level.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    chapter: '017',
    title: 'Player Animation, Cartwheels, and Missing Customers',
    date: '2026-06-13',
    stage: 'Player animation integration',
    focus:
      'Replacing the static player sprite with an animated moving player while preserving all existing gameplay components and prefab behaviour.',
    blocks: [
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Worked on the primary player movement animation today. This turned out to be a hefty task, because I needed to make sure everything matched the original player sprite setup, only now with an Animator attached.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'The animation itself was not the hard part. The real work was making sure the animated player prefab still had all the important gameplay pieces attached: movement, input, respawning, lives, score, inventories, projectile spawning, and the weather foot effects.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'I forgot to set my Z freeze constraints, so the player decided cartwheels were the way to go. Then, because of a default gravity scale of 1, jumping sent the player straight through the world. I also managed to break the customers. This was not code-related; it was me removing things I thought we did not need. Nothing major, only their graphics.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'pullquote',
        text: 'Nothing major, only their graphics.',
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'About halfway through the coding session, Unity decided to use about 16 GB of RAM, only around two-thirds of my available memory. I am not sure what was going on, because it usually peaks around 5–6 GB, but it caused quite a stir for the laptop and needed a reboot. Once rebooted, everything started behaving as expected again.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'note',
        title: 'Unity gremlin of the day',
        text: 'The player animation work was mostly prefab and component alignment rather than code. Missing Rigidbody2D constraints, default gravity values, and removed customer graphics caused more trouble than the actual Animator setup.',
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'The moving player animation is now working. I still need to tweak the animation speed so it better matches the player movement speed, but that should mostly be a case of adjusting the animation samples.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Tomorrow I will start on a flying meanie, mainly to encourage the player to keep moving. The core loop already works, so now it is about adding enough pressure and variety to make the levels feel alive.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'note',
        title: "Today's gameplay win",
        text: 'The player now has a working movement animation while keeping the existing gameplay systems intact.',
      },
      {
        type: 'next',
        title: 'Flying Meanie Pressure',
        text: 'Next up is building the first flying meanie so the player has another reason to move through the level instead of waiting safely on platforms.',
      },
    ],
  },
];

const getEntryId = (entry: DiaryEntry) => `chapter-${entry.chapter}`;

const latestEntry = courierEntries[courierEntries.length - 1];
const indexedEntries = [...courierEntries].reverse();
---

<BaseLayout
  title='Courier 16 Diary | Eddie Saunders'
  description='Build diary for Courier 16, a game development project by Eddie Saunders.'
>
  <section class='page-hero code-hero'>
    <p class='eyebrow'>Diary of a Game</p>
    <h1>Courier 16</h1>
    <p>
      A compact Unity side-scrolling delivery platformer about getting the
      package to the end of each route. This diary follows the project from
      early concept through prototype, level design, polish, WebGL build, and
      release.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class='project-showcase'>
    <div class='project-showcase-heading'>
      <p class='eyebrow'>Quick index</p>
      <h2>Latest and past entries</h2>
      <p>
        Jump straight to the newest Courier 16 update or browse the diary by
        chapter.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class='project-grid'>
      <article class='project-card'>
        <p class='project-type'>Latest entry</p>
        <h3>
          Chapter {latestEntry.chapter}: {latestEntry.title}
        </h3>
        <p>
          {latestEntry.date}
          <br />
          {latestEntry.stage}
        </p>

        <div class='project-links'>
          <a href={`#${getEntryId(latestEntry)}`}>Read Latest</a>
        </div>

        <span>{latestEntry.focus}</span>
      </article>

      <article class='project-card'>
        <p class='project-type'>Entry index</p>
        <h3>Courier 16 chapters</h3>

        <div class='diary-index-list'>
          {
            indexedEntries.map((entry) => (
              <a href={`#${getEntryId(entry)}`}>
                <span>
                  {entry.date} · Chapter {entry.chapter}
                </span>
                <strong>{entry.title}</strong>
              </a>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='development-log'>
    <header class='development-log__header'>
      <p class='eyebrow'>Development log</p>
      <h2>Building Courier 16</h2>
      <p>
        These chapters follow Courier 16 from rough idea to playable release.
        Each one focuses on a decision, problem, milestone, or lesson from the
        build rather than acting as a raw changelog.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class='diary-timeline'>
      {
        courierEntries.map((entry) => (
          <article class='diary-entry' id={getEntryId(entry)}>
            <header class='diary-entry__header'>
              <div class='diary-entry__meta-row'>
                <span>{entry.date}</span>
                <span>{entry.stage}</span>
              </div>

              <h3>
                <span>Chapter {entry.chapter}</span>
                {entry.title}
              </h3>

              <p class='diary-entry__focus'>
                <strong>Focus:</strong> {entry.focus}
              </p>
            </header>

            <div class='diary-entry__body'>
              {entry.blocks.map((block) => {
                if (block.type === 'paragraph') {
                  return (
                    <p>
                      {block.content.map((part) => {
                        if (part.href) {
                          return (
                            <a
                              href={part.href}
                              target='_blank'
                              rel='noopener noreferrer'
                            >
                              {part.strong ? (
                                <strong>{part.text}</strong>
                              ) : (
                                part.text
                              )}
                            </a>
                          );
                        }

                        if (part.strong) return <strong>{part.text}</strong>;
                        if (part.em) return <em>{part.text}</em>;
                        if (part.code) return <code>{part.text}</code>;

                        return part.text;
                      })}
                    </p>
                  );
                }

                if (block.type === 'pullquote') {
                  return (
                    <aside class='diary-pullquote'>
                      <p>{block.text}</p>
                    </aside>
                  );
                }

                if (block.type === 'figure') {
                  return (
                    <figure class='diary-figure'>
                      <img src={block.src} alt={block.alt} />
                      <figcaption>{block.caption}</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                  );
                }

                if (block.type === 'note') {
                  return (
                    <aside class='diary-note'>
                      <p class='diary-note__label'>Build note</p>
                      <h4>{block.title}</h4>
                      <p>{block.text}</p>
                    </aside>
                  );
                }

                if (block.type === 'next') {
                  return (
                    <aside class='next-step'>
                      <p class='next-step__label'>Next</p>
                      <h4>{block.title}</h4>
                      <p>{block.text}</p>
                    </aside>
                  );
                }

                return null;
              })}
            </div>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
